8 Section 14. KRS 218A.278 is amended to read as follows:
9 (1) As used in[For the purposes of] this section:
10 (a) "Analyze" means to apply scientific and mathematical measures to determine
11 meaningful patterns and associations in data. "Analyze" includes descriptive
12 analysis to examine historical data, predictive analysis to examine future
13 probabilities and trends, and prescriptive analysis to examine how future
14 decisions may impact the population and trends; and
15 (b) "Pilot program" means a program in a county or set of counties, or a subset or
16 subsets of the population, as designated by the Cabinet for Health and Family
17 Services and the Office of Drug Control Policy for analyzing the effectiveness
18 of substance abuse treatment services in Kentucky.
19 (2) The general purpose of this section is to assist in the development of a pilot
20 program to analyze the outcomes and effectiveness of substance abuse treatment
21 programs in order to ensure that the Commonwealth is:
22 (a) Addressing appropriate risk and protective factors for substance abuse in a
23 defined population;
24 (b) Using approaches that have been shown to be effective;
25 (c) Intervening early at important stages and transitions;
26 (d) Intervening in appropriate settings and domains; and
27 (e) Managing programs effectively.
Page 52 of 55
BR140200.100 - 1402 - XXXX 3/10/2026 2:38 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1402
1 (3) Sources of data for the pilot program shall include, at a minimum, claims under the
2 Kentucky Department for Medicaid Services, the electronic monitoring system for
3 controlled substances established under KRS 218A.202, and the Department of
4 Workers' Claims[ within the Education and Labor Cabinet].
5 (4) As funds are available, the Cabinet for Health and Family Services and the Office
6 of Drug Control Policy shall initiate a pilot program to determine, collect, and
7 analyze performance measurement data for substance abuse treatment services to
8 determine practices that reduce frequency of relapse, provide better outcomes for
9 patients, hold patients accountable, and control health costs related to substance
10 abuse.
11 (5) By December 31, 2016, the Cabinet for Health and Family Services and the Office
12 of Drug Control Policy shall issue a joint report to the Legislative Research
13 Commission and the Office of the Governor that:
14 (a) Details the findings of the pilot program;
15 (b) Includes recommendations based on the pilot program's results for optimizing
16 substance abuse treatment services; and
17 (c) Includes recommendations for the continued application of analytics to further
18 augment Kentucky's approach to fighting substance abuse in the future.
19 Section 15. KRS 304.13-167 is amended to read as follows:
20 (1) Every workers' compensation insurer shall adhere to a uniform classification system
21 and uniform experience rating system filed with the commissioner by an advisory
22 organization designated by the commissioner.
23 (2) Every workers' compensation insurer shall report its experience in accordance with
24 the statistical plans and other reporting requirements in use by an advisory
25 organization designated by the commissioner.
26 (3) A workers' compensation insurer may develop subclassifications of the uniform
27 classification system upon which rates may be made. These subclassifications and
Page 53 of 55
BR140200.100 - 1402 - XXXX 3/10/2026 2:38 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1402
1 their filing shall be subject to the provisions of this chapter applicable to filings
2 generally.
3 (4) A workers' compensation insurer may develop rating plans which identify loss
4 experience as a factor to be used. These rating plans and their filing shall be subject
5 to the provisions of this chapter applicable to filings generally.
6 (5) The commissioner shall disapprove subclassifications, rating plans, or other
7 variations from manual rules filed by a workers' compensation insurer if the insurer
8 fails to demonstrate that the data thereby produced can be reported consistent with
9 the uniform classification system and experience rating system and in such a
10 fashion so as to allow for the application of experience rating filed by the advisory
11 organization.
12 (6) The commissioner shall approve rating plans for workers' compensation insurance
13 that give specific identifiable consideration in the setting of rates to employers who
14 implement a drug-free workplace program pursuant to administrative regulations
15 adopted by the Department of Workers' Claims[ in the Education and Labor
16 Cabinet]. The plans shall take effect January 1, 2008, shall be actuarially sound, and
17 shall state the savings anticipated to result from such drug-free workplace
18 programs. The credit shall be at least five percent (5%) unless the commissioner
19 determines that five percent (5%) is actuarially unsound. The commissioner is also
20 authorized to develop a schedule of premium credits for workers' compensation
21 insurance for employers who have safety programs that contain certain criteria for
22 safety programs. The commissioner shall consult with the commissioner of the
23 Department of Workers' Claims[ in the Education and Labor Cabinet] in setting
24 such criteria. A drug-free workplace credit under this subsection shall not be
25 available to employers who receive a credit under KRS 304.13-412 or KRS Chapter
26 351.
